habitat_description:
Great Plains:
Although some sources (e.g. Wilson and Ruff 1999) list this species as present in Arizona, Hoffmeister (1986) regarded the inclusion of this species in the fauna of Arizona as "most questionable." The only record for that state in from the first half of the 20th century (Little 1938). As a result, Oliveira (1998) does not include Arizona within this species' range.
This endangered cat can be found in tropical and subtropical forest thickets throughout its range from Mexico to northern Argentina (Wilson and Ruff 1999). In Texas, a handful of individuals exist in dense, thorny thickets of cacti, mesquite, catclaw, granjeno, and other spinny brush (Schmidly 2004). They move along watercourses, cliff bases and thickets using cover of vegetation and rocky outcrops to mask their movements. They inhabit mesquite woodlands in the northern part of the range and pine/oak wet tropical forest in southern areas (Wilson and Ruff 1999).
